  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 하도(河圖) : '
    value: 옛 중국의 복희(伏羲) 때에 황하(黃河)에서 용마(龍馬)가 나왔는데 그 등에 그림을 나타내고 있었는데 이것을 보고 8괘(卦)를 그렸다 함. 《주역 계사(周易繫辭)》
  - key: '[주-D002] 낙서(洛書) : '
    value: 하(夏)의 우왕이 홍수를 다스릴 때에 낙수(洛水)에서 신귀(神龜)가 등과 전신에 그림을 나타내고 나왔다는 것. 《한서 오행지(漢書五行志)》
english:
  title: On Why Qin Shihuang Did Not Burn the Book of Changes
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    It is recorded that Qin Shihuang, wishing to render the common people ignorant, buried Confucian scholars alive and burned the Classic of Poetry and Classic of History, yet he alone refrained from burning the Book of Changes, treating it merely as a manual for divination. I believe this was the will of Heaven, not the will of Qin Shihuang. Why do I say this?

    If Qin Shihuang truly wished to make the people ignorant, burning the Classics and burying the scholars, then among the Five Classics, none surpasses the Book of Changes attributed to Fuxi in its wisdom and mystical power. How could he alone preserve this book, thereby enriching his people's wisdom and exalting the sage? If his purpose was merely divination, consider this: divination can only be mastered by those who deeply understand the Changes, and those who deeply understand the Changes are followers of the Confucian way. Thus his previous intent to bury the scholars was contradicted. Moreover, if he sought to preserve people while destroying books, the same logic would apply to all other classics—which negates his burning of the Poetry and History.

    Furthermore, Heaven brought forth mystical things: the yarrow and the tortoise. These were joined by the Diagram of the Yellow River and the Writing of the Luo River, continued by the appearance of sages. The sage, receiving Heaven's mandate, drew forth the eight trigrams and established the Creative and Receptive principles, thereby opening the path to divine understanding. Thus the Book of Changes came into being. Does not the Classic teach: "When Heaven and Earth are complete, the Changes exists within them; when the Changes does not manifest, Heaven and Earth themselves nearly cease"?

    From this we see that the Book of Changes is born of Heaven itself. If Heaven wished to destroy it, it would be as if it were never created. Yet if Heaven did not wish its destruction, how could one mere mortal emperor overcome the will of Heaven and burn it, thereby extinguishing the Way of Heaven and Earth? Therefore I say: this preservation was the will of Heaven, not the will of Qin Shihuang. Were it otherwise, how could the Book of Changes remain a scripture of the divine and an instrument of cosmic order?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Diagram of the Yellow River and the Writing of the Luo River are legendary cosmological symbols associated with the origins of the Book of Changes. According to tradition, these sacred diagrams appeared on the backs of mythical creatures and provided the basis for understanding universal principles.
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Classics (Wujing) in the Confucian tradition are the Classic of Poetry, Classic of History, Book of Rites, Spring and Autumn Annals, and Book of Changes.
